children.subject:
This past semester I took 133 but not Data 100. As someone who took CS61A/B prior to 133, it honestly didn't teach much skills wise. In my *personal* opinion, all the concepts in 133 that are taught can easily be self-learned. I think we spent a whole week talking about how git and github works, and it talks a lot about file structures and things of that nature. You'll mostly be learning about how R works as a language and how to apply it to very basic problems (like rolling a dice, using pretty basic packages to plot data) as opposed to real data analysis.

It's quite easy for people who have CS skill to get a good grade in the course, though. TLDR: If you strictly want to learn R, 133 definitely lets you do practice with that, but it teaches about the language and not necessarily statistical/data analysis concepts.

history.content: Do 100, you'll get a lot more out of the class in terms of DS skills..

I am taking data science/stat courses for fun and out of a utilitarianism perspective for potential big data from experimental research. I have prior python experience and I am going to take CS C100 next semester. However, I also heard that R could be very useful. I am wondering if / too which degree there is any overlap between CS C100 and Stat 133? If I choose one out of the two, which one would be better in the sense that it would be fun + useful? Thanks!
history.subject: Stat 133 vs/& CS C100
